{
  "doc_id": "37622",
  "text": "At the end of this stage, the GFP acquires its characteristic absorbance and fluorescence properties [CITATION_1] . Although only a hexapeptide domain within the chromophore is responsible for the fluorescence yield of the GFP, the entire structure of the protein is required to protect the chromophore from the collisional quenching of oxygen and water that promotes photobleaching [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Without such a protection, denatured GFPs or small proteolytic fragments carrying the chromophore are exposed to jostling water dipoles, paramagnetic oxygen molecules, or cis-trans isomerization, and therefore are totally non-fluorescent [CITATION_5] .",
